{"parse":{"title":"Focale","pageid":5013797,"revid":835299214,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tleft\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:172px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Focale_scarf.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ac/Focale_scarf.jpg/170px-Focale_scarf.jpg\" width=\"170\" height=\"128\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ac/Focale_scarf.jpg/255px-Focale_scarf.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ac/Focale_scarf.jpg/340px-Focale_scarf.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2272\" data-file-height=\"1704\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Focale_scarf.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><i>Focale</i> on a <a href=\"/wiki/Classical_reenactment\" title=\"Classical reenactment\">Roman military reenactor</a></div></div></div>\n<p>The <i><b>focale</b></i> (plural <i>focalia</i>), also known as a <i><b>sudarium</b></i> (\"sweat cloth\"),<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> was a woolen or linen <a href=\"/wiki/Scarf\" title=\"Scarf\">scarf</a> worn by <a href=\"/wiki/Military_of_ancient_Rome\" title=\"Military of ancient Rome\">ancient Roman military</a> personnel. It protected the neck from chafing by the armor.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The <i>focale</i> is depicted widely in military scenes from <a href=\"/wiki/Roman_art\" title=\"Roman art\">Roman art</a>, such as the <a href=\"/wiki/Relief_sculpture\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Relief sculpture\">relief sculpture</a> on the <a href=\"/wiki/Arch_of_Septimius_Severus\" title=\"Arch of Septimius Severus\">Arch of Septimius Severus</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/Roman_Forum\" title=\"Roman Forum\">Roman Forum</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> and <a href=\"/wiki/Trajan%27s_Column\" title=\"Trajan&#39;s Column\">Trajan's Column</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> It is shown loosely knotted in the front, but is sometimes visible with the ends tucked inside the cuirass.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:402px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:018_Conrad_Cichorius,_Die_Reliefs_der_Traianss%C3%A4ule,_Tafel_XVIII.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/018_Conrad_Cichorius%2C_Die_Reliefs_der_Traianss%C3%A4ule%2C_Tafel_XVIII.jpg/400px-018_Conrad_Cichorius%2C_Die_Reliefs_der_Traianss%C3%A4ule%2C_Tafel_XVIII.jpg\" width=\"400\" height=\"258\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/018_Conrad_Cichorius%2C_Die_Reliefs_der_Traianss%C3%A4ule%2C_Tafel_XVIII.jpg/600px-018_Conrad_Cichorius%2C_Die_Reliefs_der_Traianss%C3%A4ule%2C_Tafel_XVIII.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/018_Conrad_Cichorius%2C_Die_Reliefs_der_Traianss%C3%A4ule%2C_Tafel_XVIII.jpg/800px-018_Conrad_Cichorius%2C_Die_Reliefs_der_Traianss%C3%A4ule%2C_Tafel_XVIII.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2000\" data-file-height=\"1290\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:018_Conrad_Cichorius,_Die_Reliefs_der_Traianss%C3%A4ule,_Tafel_XVIII.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><i>Focalia</i> worn by cavalry troopers and some infantry on a panel from Trajan's Column</div></div></div>\n<p>In Latin literature, <i>focale</i> is a general word for a scarf or wrapping for the throat.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> A <i>focale</i> was one of the gifts that might be given for the December festival of <a href=\"/wiki/Saturnalia\" title=\"Saturnalia\">Saturnalia</a>, according to <a href=\"/wiki/Martial\" title=\"Martial\">Martial</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> In one of his <a href=\"/wiki/Satires_(Horace)\" title=\"Satires (Horace)\">satires</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Horace\" title=\"Horace\">Horace</a> lists <i>focalia</i> among the \"badges of illness\" <i>(insignia morbi)</i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> In describing the correct attire for public speaking, <a href=\"/wiki/Quintilian\" title=\"Quintilian\">Quintilian</a> advises against wearing a <i>focale</i>, unless required by poor health.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Although a <i>sudarium</i> often is used as a <a href=\"/wiki/Handkerchief\" title=\"Handkerchief\">handkerchief</a>, it can be worn like the <i>focale</i> as a <a href=\"/wiki/Neckerchief\" title=\"Neckerchief\">neckerchief</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> When <a href=\"/wiki/Suetonius\" title=\"Suetonius\">Suetonius</a> describes the overly casual attire of <a href=\"/wiki/Nero\" title=\"Nero\">Nero</a>, the emperor is barefoot, unbelted, and dressed in <a href=\"/wiki/Formal_wear\" title=\"Formal wear\">evening wear</a> <i>(<a href=\"/wiki/Synthesis_(clothing)\" title=\"Synthesis (clothing)\">synthesis</a>)</i>, with a <i>sudarium</i> around his neck.<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> In late antiquity, <i>orarium</i> (Greek <i><a href=\"/wiki/Orarion\" title=\"Orarion\">orarion</a></i>) might be synonymous with <i>focale</i>, as in the description of military attire in the <i><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Vision_of_Dorotheus&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Vision of Dorotheus (page does not exist)\">Vision of Dorotheus</a></i>, and in a <a href=\"/wiki/Papyri\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Papyri\">papyrus</a> (dated 350\u2013450 AD) listing military clothes.<sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The <i>focale</i> is sometimes seen as one of the precursors of the <a href=\"/wiki/Necktie\" title=\"Necktie\">necktie</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Cesare_Vecellio\" title=\"Cesare Vecellio\">Cesare Vecellio</a> (1530\u20131606) mentions the <i>focale</i>, calling it a <i>cravata</i> (<a href=\"/wiki/Cravat\" title=\"Cravat\">cravat</a>), as worn by Roman soldiers in his book on the history of fashion.<sup id=\"cite_ref-14\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> It has been compared to the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Amice\" title=\"Amice\">amice</a></i> <i>(amictus)</i> worn by Roman Catholic priests, which is depicted from the 6th century onward, as in the <a href=\"/wiki/Ravenna_mosaics\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ravenna mosaics\">Ravenna mosaics</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-15\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-15\">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Focale&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Jason R. Abdal, <i>Four Days in September: The Battle of Teutoburg</i> (Trafford, 2013), p. 167.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Nic Fields, <i>The Roman Army of the Principate 27 BC-AD 117</i> (Osprey, 2009), p. 25.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Richard Brilliant, \"The Arch of Septimius Severus in the Roman Forum,\" <i>Memoirs of the American Academy</i> 29 (1967), pp. 139, 142, 155, 156, 158, 184, 186, 190, 197, 203, 210.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">John Hungerford Pollen, <i>A Description of the Trajan Column</i> (London, 1874), p. 111.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Abdal, <i>Four Days in September,</i> p. 167; Liza Cleland, Glenys Davies, and Lloyd Llewellyn-Jones, entry on \"scarf,\" <i>Greek and Roman Dress from A to Z</i> (Routledge, 2007), p. 166.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antoine_Mongez\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"fr:Antoine Mongez\">Antoine Mongez</a>, \"Recherches sur les habillemens des anciens,\" <i>Histoire et m\u00e9moires de l'Institute Royal de France</i> 4 (1818), pp. 295\u2013295.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Martial 14.137 (142).</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-8\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Horace, <i>Satires</i> 2.8.255; article on \"Dress,\" <i>A Concise Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</i>, edited by F. Warre Cornish (London, 1898), p. 259.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-9\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-9\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Quintilian <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Quintilian/Institutio_Oratoria/11C*.html#3.144\">11.3.144.</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Legwarmers\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Legwarmers\">Legwarmers</a> <i>(fascias quibus crura vestiuntur)</i> and <a href=\"/wiki/Earmuffs\" title=\"Earmuffs\">earmuffs</a> <i>(aurium ligamenta)</i> are likewise to be avoided.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-10\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-10\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Mongez, \"Recherches sur les habillemens des anciens,\" p. 295.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-11\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-11\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Suetonius, <i>Nero</i> 51; Mongez, \"Recherches sur les habillemens des anciens,\" p. 295.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-12\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-12\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><i>SB</i> VI.9570.5; <a href=\"/wiki/Jan_Bremmer\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Jan Bremmer\">Jan Bremmer</a>, \"An Imperial Palace Guard in Heaven: The Date of the Vision of Dorotheus,\" <i>Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Papyrologie und Epigraphik</i> 75 (1988), p. 86.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-13\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-13\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Daniel K. Hall, <i>How to Tie a Tie: Choosing, Coordinating, and Knotting Your Neckwear</i> (Sterling, 2008), p. 8.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-14\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-14\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Oscar Lenius, <i>The Well-Dressed Gentleman</i> (LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster, 2010), p. 93.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-15\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-15\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Charles Panati, <i>Sacred Origins of Profound Things</i> (Arkana, 1996), <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=8xKkiDz4qCwC&amp;pg=PT146&amp;dq=focale+roman+soldier&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ei=1XgVUunPIqeh2AXx-YGADA&amp;ved=0CFoQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&amp;q=focale%20roman%20soldier&amp;f=false\">n.p.</a>; Mongez, \"Recherches sur les habillemens des anciens,\" p. 296.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1288\nCached time: 20180910005110\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.052 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.072 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 248/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 302/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 70/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 5623/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.007/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 670 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   35.873      1 -total\n 65.48%   23.488      1 Template:Reflist\n 34.36%   12.325      1 Template:Italic_title\n  4.95%    1.774      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:5013797-0!canonical and timestamp 20180910005110 and revision id 835299214\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[{"lang":"cs","url":"https://cs.wikipedia.org/wiki/Focale","langname":"Czech","autonym":"\u010de\u0161tina","*":"Focale"},{"lang":"de","url":"https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Focale","langname":"German","autonym":"Deutsch","*":"Focale"},{"lang":"es","url":"https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Focale","langname":"Spanish","autonym":"espa\u00f1ol","*":"Focale"},{"lang":"fr","url":"https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Focale_(v%C3%AAtement)","langname":"French","autonym":"fran\u00e7ais","*":"Focale (v\u00eatement)"},{"lang":"lt","url":"https://lt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fokal%C4%97","langname"